Analysis of U.S. Homicide Reports (1980-2014)¶

By Shashwat Joshi¶

Introduction¶

According to Statista, there were a total of 17,284 reported murder and non-negligent manslaughter cases in the U.S in 2017. To improve the response to homicides, analysis of key factors relating to these crimes is required. This tutorial is using dataset of U.S. Homicide Reports from 1980-2014 and aims to provide analysis on key factors like age, sex, race and state. This tutorial is also using dataset of U.S. Census demographic data of 2015 which will help in providing relation between homicides and population and poverty. Although homicides have reduced drastically over the years, there is still a lot of path to cover.

Contents¶

  1. Data collection and cleaning
  2. Data analysis and visualisation
  3. Linear Regression and Hypothesis testing
  4. Conclusion
  5. References

2. Data visualisation and analysis¶

This part of tutorial deals with data analysis and visualization using pie charts, plots and maps.

2.1. Homicide cases solved v/s unsolved¶

In this part of tutorial, we will analyse the percentage of crimes solved across 1980 - 2014. This will help us understand what percentage of cases remain unsolved as a mystery.

2.1.1. Data preparation¶

Firstly, we will store Crime Solved in new DataFrame and then count the number of Crimes Solved by making use of pandas library functions - groupby and count.

You can know more about Pandas groupby: https://pandas.pydata.org/pandas-docs/stable/generated/pandas.DataFrame.groupby.html and Pandas count: https://pandas.pydata.org/pandas-docs/stable/generated/pandas.DataFrame.count.html

In [6]:
solved = pd.DataFrame(data, columns = ['Crime Solved'])
resolution = solved.groupby(data['Crime Solved'])['Crime Solved'].count()

2.1.2. Data visualization and analysis¶

Now we plot the data on a pie chart to show percentage of homicide cases solved over the years.

In [7]:
ax = resolution.plot(kind = 'pie',
title = 'Crimes solved from 1980 - 2014 (in %)',

autopct='%.2f')
ax.set_ylabel('')

2.2. Homicide cases by Race¶

In this part of tutorial, we will analyse the race division among perpetrators and victims across 1980 - 2014 and try to find out the the race having highest victim and perpetrator and also answer to who killed whom in terms of race.

2.2.1. Data preparation¶

Firstly, we will store Race in new DataFrame and then count the race which victims and perpetrator belonged to by making use of pandas library functions - groupby and count. In the below step we will be doing data preparation for 3 plots - Pie chart of Victim race, Perpetrator race and a Bar plot showing relation between Victim and Perpetrator of each race. In these plots, we will have to eliminate cases where any of the race is Unknown to provide better analysis.

In [8]:
race = pd.DataFrame(data, columns = ['Victim Race', 'Perpetrator Race'])
race = race[race['Victim Race'] != 'Unknown'] # Remove Unknown for Victim race
race = race[race['Perpetrator Race'] != 'Unknown'] # Remove Unknown for Perpetrator race
racevic = race.groupby(['Victim Race'])['Victim Race'].count() # DataFrame with Count for Victim race
raceperp = race.groupby(['Perpetrator Race'])['Perpetrator Race'].count() # DataFrame with Count for Perpetrator race
racerel = race.groupby(['Victim Race', 'Perpetrator Race'])['Victim Race'].count() # DataFrame for relation

age = pd.DataFrame(data, columns = ['Victim Age', 'Perpetrator Age'])
age = age[age['Perpetrator Age'] != '0'] # Remove Perpetrator Age is 0
age = age[age['Perpetrator Age'] != ' '] # Remove Perpetrator Age is ' '
age = age[age['Victim Age'] != '0'] # Remove Victim Age is 0
age = age[age['Victim Age'] != ' '] # Remove Victim Age is ' '
# Convert Perpetrator and Victim Age type to int
age['Perpetrator Age'] = age['Perpetrator Age'].astype(int)
age['Victim Age'] = age['Victim Age'].astype(int)

2.5. Homicide cases by State¶

In this part of tutorial, we will see the number of homicides for each state. We will also find out the top 5 most unsafe states across the U.S and relationship between number of homicides and population, poverty of a state.

2.5.1. Data preparation¶

Firstly, we will store State in new DataFrame and then count the number of incidents for each state from 1980 - 2014 by making use of pandas library functions - groupby and count. Similarly we will also extract total population of each state of U.S. in 100,000.

In [20]:
state = pd.DataFrame(data, columns = ['State', 'Incident']) # DataFrame with just 2 columns
count_state = state.groupby(data['State']).count() # Count of each State
count_state2 = count_state[['Incident']].reset_index()
states = pd.DataFrame(count_state2, columns = ['State', 'Incident']) # Transfering data to this new DataFrame
states['Perc'] = states['Incident']*100/states['Incident'].sum() # Percentage of Homicide cases
states.head()

2.5.3. Data Visualization of State on Choropleth Map¶

In this part, we will provide 2 Data Visualizations using Choropleth Map. We will be using a python library called Folium to display the maps. Folium allows us to display data on map in different ways using sattelite, terrain, heat and Choropleth maps which are completely customizable. More info about Folium can be found at https://python-visualization.github.io/folium/docs-v0.6.0/. Also https://python-visualization.github.io/folium/quickstart.html has some cool implementations. To import U.S. states with boundaries, we will import a geo-json file called us-states.json which can be downloaded from https://raw.githubusercontent.com/python-visualization/folium/master/examples/data/us-states.json. The 2 maps we will display will be:

  1. State wise Homicide percentage
  2. State wise population percentage

Both of these maps will help us look at the correlations between population and humicide rate.

Below is the first Map showing State wise Homicide Rate.

In [26]:
# Path for json file
state_geo = os.path.join('us-states.json')
# Initialize map location and zoom level
m = folium.Map(location=[45, -100], zoom_start=3.5)
# Map type will be choropleth to graphically show the homicide percentage state wise  
folium.Choropleth(
    geo_data=state_geo,
    name='choropleth',
    data=states,
    columns=['State', 'Perc'],
    key_on='feature.properties.name',
    fill_color='Reds',
    fill_opacity=0.8,
    line_opacity=0.6,
    legend_name='Homicide Rate (%)'
).add_to(m)

folium.LayerControl().add_to(m)
m
Out[26]:

It can be seen in the above map that California, Texas, New York and Florida are darker than the other states showing high Homicide rates.

3. Linear Regression and Hypothesis testing¶

This part of tutorial deals with doing linear regression and prediction testing. In the process of Linear Regression, we take sample data and predict future data based on the patterns. We are going to perform 2 separate Linear Regression and compare them using F-Test for Hypothesis testing. First Linear Regression will be on Homicide cases by year and second on Homicide cases relation to Year, month and State.

3.1. Linear Regression on Homicide cases by year¶

Below we will create Linear Regression model for Number of Homicides per year and plot the Regression line with sample data. We will be utilising Linear Regression library to create and predict the model.

Link to the documentation: https://scikit-learn.org/stable/modules/generated/sklearn.linear_model.LinearRegression.html

In [31]:
# Linear Regression
yearsval = years2['Year'].values
X = [[x] for x in yearsval]
Y = [[y] for y in years2['Incident'].values]
lregfit = LinearRegression().fit(X, Y)

print("On an average, Number of homicides decreases by " + str(-1*lregfit.coef_[0][0]) + " every year in the U.S.")
print("In the U.S. Predicted Number of homicides in 2018, 2019 and 2020 will be " + str(lregfit.predict(2018)[0][0]) +", "+ str(lregfit.predict(2019)[0][0]) +" and "+ str(lregfit.predict(2020)[0][0]))

# Predicted values
pre_count = []
for x in yearsval:
    pre_count.append(lregfit.predict(x)[0][0])
years2['pre_count'] = pd.Series(pre_count, index = years2.index)

# Plotting Linear Regression
plt.plot(yearsval, years2['Incident'], color='red',)
plt.plot(yearsval, years2['pre_count'], color='blue')
plt.xlabel("Year")
plt.ylabel("Number of Homicides")
plt.title("Number of Homicides per Year")

On an average, Number of homicides decreases by 214.409243697 every year in the U.S.
In the U.S. Predicted Number of homicides in 2018, 2019 and 2020 will be 13738.9487395, 13524.5394958 and 13310.1302521

3.3. Hypothesis testing¶

In Hypothesis testing, we consider the result we are trying to achieve as alternative hypothesis. Null hypothesis is the negative of this alternative hypothesis. So when we perform the analysis and the results disprove the null hypothesis, we reject the null hypothesis thereby proving alternative hypothesis correct. You can learn more about Null and alternative hypothesis here: https://explorable.com/null-hypothesis. Our Null Hypothesis will be that We will not be able to improve model's accuracy when using multiple factors for relation Year, month and state as opposed to only year and there does not exist interaction between the factors of regression.

For Hypothesis testing, we will be using F-test. F-test will help us compare which linear regression model fits better. You can learn more about F-test here: http://blog.minitab.com/blog/adventures-in-statistics-2/understanding-analysis-of-variance-anova-and-the-f-test. There is a special library in stats model called ANOVA (Analysis of Variance) for conducting F-tests on multiple regressions which we will be using here. Additional information about ANOVA can be found in its official specification here: https://www.statsmodels.org/stable/anova.html.

First Linear Regression model is a one factor ANOVA where only factor is Year whereas Second Linear Regression model is a three factor ANOVA where the three factors are Year, Month and State.

The sum_sq value of Year for year-only model is much higher (1.641176e+08) than interaction model with all three factors (7.987322e+04). This makes sense as number of homicides is increasing at different rates in different states in different months. The F value of Year for year-only model is much higher (38.928523) than interaction model with all three factors (0.799094). This disproves the null hypothesis hence We will be able to improve model's accuracy when using multiple factors for relation Year, month and state as opposed to only year and there does exist interaction between the factors of regression.

4. Conclusion¶

Homicides are a continuous threat to people across the world. This tutorial throws light on the pattern and trends across the U.S. Earlier such in depth analysis was impossible but with advancement of technology and specially advancements in the field of Data Science we are now able to see key trends such as average age of Perpetrators, Racial crimes and percentage of unsolved crimes we were unaware of and make informed decisions to increase safety of all citizens.

Key take aways:¶

  1. Between 1980 - 2014 still 29.8% of Homicide cases remain unsolved in the U.S.
  2. Majority of victims are white as well as majority of perpetrators are white.
  3. Inter-racial homicides are not the most common type. White-White and Black-Black crimes are major.
  4. More than 75% of victims are male.
  5. Same sex crimes are the most common.
  6. Highest number of victims belong to age 22 and the victim count is extremely high between 19 and 25.
  7. Highest number of perpetrators belong to age 20 and the perpetrator count is extremely high between 17 and 20 which shows many perpetrators are very young.
  8. Average age of perpetrator is just 30 years.
  9. Strong corelation between population and homicide rate per state.
  10. Also Strong corelation between Poverty and homicide rate per state.
  11. Number of homicides is decreasing each year by 214.

There is a lot of information present in this dataset that we were not able to explore in this tutorial. So I will encourage you to explore it further. Some interesting ideas to explore are:

  1. Relationship between Victim and Perpetrator
  2. Number of homicides relation to average response time of police of the state
  3. Number of homicides relation to per capita income of the state
